The collation of the earlier used by Jahn is by Dnebner. Their task was rendered more laborious by the strange orthography of the MSS. and their many palpable blunders. A more accurate and useful MS. is one of the tenth century (which is not however complete), in the library of Bem. There are several of the tenth and eleventh centuries, and it is clear that Persius, though he must have been but little understood ², was a good deal read among the semipagani of the mediaeval monasteries.

'Phe Satires of Persius are herc joined with those of Juvenal, according to a common practice. But except for the convenience of publication, there is no reason why they should be so. United they form a fair-sized volume, which separately they would not do except by extending the notes on either to an inordinate and useless length. Persius, though older than Juvenal, yet, as being less read and of less importunos, is usually and rightly put after him.

It is easy to write long notes on such authors as these3 indeed the difficulty is to write at moderate length,· even without the prac- tice, which I think objectionable, of overlaying the text with an embarrassing heap of references.
